# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: generalized-additive-models
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:generalized-additive-models/additive-model] In statistics, an **additive model** (**AM**) is a nonparametric regression method.
[src:generalized-additive-models/additive-model] Friedman and Werner Stuetzle (1981) and is an essential part of the ACE algorithm.
[src:generalized-additive-models/additive-model] The *AM* uses a one-dimensional smoother to build a restricted class of nonparametric regression models.
[src:generalized-additive-models/additive-model] Because of this, it is less affected by the curse of dimensionality than a *p*-dimensional smoother.
[src:generalized-additive-models/additive-model] Furthermore, the *AM* is more flexible than a standard linear model, while being more interpretable than a general regression surface at the cost of approximation errors.
[src:generalized-additive-models/additive-model] Problems with *AM*, like many other machine-learning methods, include model selection, overfitting, and multicollinearity.
[src:generalized-additive-models/additive-model] The functions $f_{j}(x_{ij})$ are unknown smooth functions fit from the data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/additive-model] Fitting the *AM* (i.e. the functions $f_{j}(x_{ij})$ ) can be done using the backfitting algorithm proposed by Andreas Buja, Trevor Hastie and Robert Tibshirani (1989).
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] In statistics, the **backfitting algorithm** is a simple iterative procedure used to fit a generalized additive model.
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] It was introduced in 1985 by Leo Breiman and Jerome Friedman along with generalized additive models.
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] In most cases, the backfitting algorithm is equivalent to the Gauss–Seidel method, an algorithm used for solving a certain linear system of equations.
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] where each $X_{1},X_{2},\ldots ,X_{p}$ is a variable in our p -dimensional predictor X , and Y is our outcome variable. $\epsilon$ represents our inherent error, which is assumed to have mean zero.
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] The $f_{j}$ represent unspecified smooth functions of a single $X_{j}$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] Given the flexibility in the $f_{j}$ , we typically do not have a unique solution: $\alpha$ is left unidentifiable as one can add any constants to any of the $f_{j}$ and subtract this value from $\alpha$ .
