[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] In theory, step **(b)** in the algorithm is not needed as the function estimates are constrained to sum to zero.
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] However, due to numerical issues this might become a problem in practice.
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] An exact solution of this is infeasible to calculate for large *np*, so the iterative technique of backfitting is used.
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] Looking at the abbreviated form it is easy to see the backfitting algorithm as equivalent to the Gauss–Seidel method for linear smoothing operators *S*.
[src:generalized-additive-models/backfitting-algorithm] Following, we can formulate the backfitting algorithm explicitly for the two dimensional case.
