[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] In statistics, a **generalized additive model** (**GAM**) is a generalized linear model in which the linear response variable depends linearly on unknown smooth functions of some predictor variables, and interest focuses on inference about these smooth functions.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] GAMs were originally developed by Trevor Hastie and Robert Tibshirani to blend properties of generalized linear models with additive models.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] They can be interpreted as the discriminative generalization of the naive Bayes generative model.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The model relates a univariate response variable, *Y*, to some predictor variables, *x**i*.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The functions *f**i* may be functions with a specified parametric form (for example a polynomial, or an un-penalized regression spline of a variable) or may be specified non-parametrically, or semi-parametrically, simply as 'smooth functions', to be estimated by non-parametric means.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] So a typical GAM might use a scatterplot smoothing function, such as a locally weighted mean, for *f*1(*x*1), and then use a factor model for *f*2(*x*2).
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] This flexibility to allow non-parametric fits with relaxed assumptions on the actual relationship between response and predictor, provides the potential for better fits to data than purely parametric models, but arguably with some loss of interpretability.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Unfortunately, though the Kolmogorov–Arnold representation theorem asserts the existence of a function of this form, it gives no mechanism whereby one could be constructed.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Certain constructive proofs exist, but they tend to require highly complicated (i.e. fractal) functions, and thus are not suitable for modeling approaches.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] where $\Phi$ is a smooth monotonic function.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Which is the standard formulation of a generalized additive model.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] It was then shown that the backfitting algorithm will always converge for these functions.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The GAM model class is quite broad, given that *smooth function* is a rather broad category.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] For example, a covariate $x_{j}$ may be multivariate and the corresponding $f_{j}$ a smooth function of several variables, or $f_{j}$ might be the function mapping the level of a factor to the value of a random effect.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Another example is a varying coefficient (geographic regression) term such as $z_{j}f_{j}(x_{j})$ where $z_{j}$ and $x_{j}$ are both covariates.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Or if $x_{j}(t)$ is itself an observation of a function, we might include a term such as $\int f_{j}(t)x_{j}(t)dt$ (sometimes known as a signal regression term). $f_{j}$ could also be a simple parametric function as might be used in any generalized linear model.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The model class has been generalized in several directions, notably beyond exponential family response distributions, beyond modelling of only the mean and beyond univariate data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The original GAM fitting method estimated the smooth components of the model using non-parametric smoothers (for example smoothing splines or local linear regression smoothers) via the backfitting algorithm.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Backfitting works by iterative smoothing of partial residuals and provides a very general modular estimation method capable of using a wide variety of smoothing methods to estimate the $f_{j}(x_{j})$ terms.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] A disadvantage of backfitting is that it is difficult to integrate with the estimation of the degree of smoothness of the model terms, so that in practice the user must set these, or select between a modest set of pre-defined smoothing levels.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] This full spline approach carries an $O(n^{3})$ computational cost, where n is the number of observations for the response variable, rendering it somewhat impractical for moderately large datasets.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] More recent methods have addressed this computational cost either by up front reduction of the size of the basis used for smoothing (rank reduction) or by finding sparse representations of the smooths using Markov random fields, which are amenable to the use of sparse matrix methods for computation.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] These more computationally efficient methods use GCV (or AIC or similar) or REML or take a fully Bayesian approach for inference about the degree of smoothness of the model components.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Estimating the degree of smoothness via REML can be viewed as an empirical Bayes method.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] An alternative approach with particular advantages in high dimensional settings is to use boosting, although this typically requires bootstrapping for uncertainty quantification.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] GAMs fit using bagging and boosting have been found to generally outperform GAMs fit using spline methods.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] where the $b_{jk}(x_{j})$ are known basis functions, usually chosen for good approximation theoretic properties (for example B splines or reduced rank thin plate splines), and the $\beta _{jk}$ are coefficients to be estimated as part of model fitting.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The basis dimension $K_{j}$ is chosen to be sufficiently large that we expect it to overfit the data to hand (thereby avoiding bias from model over-simplification), but small enough to retain computational efficiency.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] If $p=\sum _{j}K_{j}$ then the computational cost of model estimation this way will be $O(np^{2})$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Notice that the $f_{j}$ are only identifiable to within an intercept term (we could add any constant to $f_{1}$ while subtracting it from $f_{2}$ without changing the model predictions at all), so identifiability constraints have to be imposed on the smooth terms to remove this ambiguity.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] i.e. by insisting that the sum of each the $f_{j}$ evaluated at its observed covariate values should be zero.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Such linear constraints can most easily be imposed by reparametrization at the basis setup stage, so below it is assumed that this has been done.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Having replaced all the $f_{j}$ in the model with such basis expansions we have turned the GAM into a generalized linear model (GLM), with a model matrix that simply contains the basis functions evaluated at the observed $x_{j}$ values.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] However, because the basis dimensions, $K_{j}$ , have been chosen to be a somewhat larger than is believed to be necessary for the data, the model is over-parameterized and will overfit the data if estimated as a regular GLM.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The solution to this problem is to penalize departure from smoothness in the model fitting process, controlling the weight given to the smoothing penalties using smoothing parameters.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] For example, consider the situation in which all the smooths are univariate functions.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Writing all the parameters in one vector, $\beta$ , suppose that $D(\beta )$ is the deviance (twice the difference between saturated log likelihood and the model log likelihood) for the model.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] where the integrated square second derivative penalties serve to penalize wiggliness (lack of smoothness) of the $f_{j}$ during fitting, and the smoothing parameters $\lambda _{j}$ control the tradeoff between model goodness of fit and model smoothness.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] In the example $\lambda _{j}\to \infty$ would ensure that the estimate of $f_{j}(x_{j})$ would be a straight line in $x_{j}$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Given the basis expansion for each $f_{j}$ the wiggliness penalties can be expressed as quadratic forms in the model coefficients.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] which can be found using a penalized version of the usual iteratively reweighted least squares (IRLS) algorithm for GLMs: the algorithm is unchanged except that the sum of quadratic penalties is added to the working least squared objective at each iteration of the algorithm.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Penalization has several effects on inference, relative to a regular GLM.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] For one thing the estimates are subject to some smoothing bias, which is the price that must be paid for limiting estimator variance by penalization.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] However, if smoothing parameters are selected appropriately the (squared) smoothing bias introduced by penalization should be less than the reduction in variance that it produces, so that the net effect is a reduction in mean square estimation error, relative to not penalizing.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] A related effect of penalization is that the notion of degrees of freedom of a model has to be modified to account for the penalties' action in reducing the coefficients' freedom to vary.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] is the effective degrees of freedom matrix.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] In fact summing just the diagonal elements of F corresponding to the coefficients of $f_{j}$ gives the effective degrees of freedom for the estimate of $f_{j}$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Smoothing bias complicates interval estimation for these models, and the simplest approach turns out to involve a Bayesian approach.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Understanding this Bayesian view of smoothing also helps to understand the REML and full Bayes approaches to smoothing parameter estimation.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] At some level smoothing penalties are imposed because we believe smooth functions to be more probable than wiggly ones, and if that is true then we might as well formalize this notion by placing a prior on model wiggliness.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] (where $\phi$ is the GLM scale parameter introduced only for later convenience), but we can immediately recognize this as a multivariate normal prior with mean 0 and precision matrix $S_{\lambda }=\sum _{j}\lambda _{j}S_{j}/\phi$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Now if this prior is combined with the GLM likelihood, we find that the posterior mode for $\beta$ is exactly the ${\hat {\beta }}$ found above by penalized IRLS.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] which can be used to produce confidence/credible intervals for the smooth components, $f_{j}$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The Gaussian smoothness priors are also the basis for fully Bayesian inference with GAMs, as well as methods estimating GAMs as mixed models that are essentially empirical Bayes methods.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] So far we have treated estimation and inference given the smoothing parameters, $\lambda$ , but these also need to be estimated.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] One approach is to take a fully Bayesian approach, defining priors on the (log) smoothing parameters, and using stochastic simulation or high order approximation methods to obtain information about the posterior of the model coefficients.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] An alternative is to select the smoothing parameters to optimize a prediction error criterion such as Generalized cross validation (GCV) or the Akaike information criterion (AIC).
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Since $f(y|\beta ,\lambda )$ is just the likelihood of $\beta$ , we can view this as choosing $\lambda$ to maximize the average likelihood of random draws from the prior.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The preceding integral is usually analytically intractable but can be approximated to quite high accuracy using Laplace's method.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Smoothing parameter inference is the most computationally taxing part of model estimation/inference.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Furthermore, to obtain the derivatives of the GCV or LAML, required for optimization, involves implicit differentiation to obtain the derivatives of ${\hat {\beta }}$ w.r.t. the log smoothing parameters, and this requires some care is efficiency and numerical stability are to be maintained.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Backfit GAMs were originally provided by the `gam` function in S, now ported to the R language as the `gam` package.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The SAS proc `GAM` also provides backfit GAMs.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The recommended package in R for GAMs is `mgcv`, which stands for *mixed GAM computational vehicle*, which is based on the reduced rank approach with automatic smoothing parameter selection.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The SAS proc `GAMPL` is an alternative implementation.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] In Python, there is the PyGAM package, with similar features to R's mgcv.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Alternatively, there is `InterpretML` package, which implements a bagging and boosting approach.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Examples include the R packages `mboost`, which implements a boosting approach; `gss`, which provides the full spline smoothing methods; `VGAM` which provides vector GAMs; and `gamlss`, which provides Generalized additive model for location, scale and shape.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] `BayesX` and its R interface provides GAMs and extensions via MCMC and penalized likelihood methods.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The `INLA` software implements a fully Bayesian approach based on Markov random field representations exploiting sparse matrix methods.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] As an example of how models can be estimated in practice with software, consider R package `mgcv`.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] In common with most R modelling functions `gam` expects a model formula to be supplied, specifying the model structure to fit.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The response variable is given to the left of the `~` while the specification of the linear predictor is given to the right.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] `gam` sets up bases and penalties for the smooth terms, estimates the model including its smoothing parameters and, in standard R fashion, returns a *fitted model object*, which can then be interrogated using various helper functions, such as `summary`, `plot`, `predict`, and `AIC`.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] This simple example has used several default settings which it is important to be aware of.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] For example a Gaussian distribution and identity link has been assumed, and the smoothing parameter selection criterion was GCV.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Also the smooth terms were represented using `penalized thin plate regression splines', and the basis dimension for each was set to 10 (implying a maximum of 9 degrees of freedom after identifiability constraints have been imposed).
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] A second example illustrates how we can control these things.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] using REML smoothing parameter selection, and we expect $f_{1}$ to be a relatively complicated function which we would like to model with a penalized cubic regression spline.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] which uses a basis size of 100 for the smooth of t .
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The specification of distribution and link function uses the `family' objects that are standard when fitting GLMs in R or S.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Note that Gaussian random effects can also be added to the linear predictor.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] These examples are only intended to give a very basic flavour of the way that GAM software is used, for more detail refer to the software documentation for the various packages and the references below.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] As with any statistical model it is important to check the model assumptions of a GAM.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Residual plots should be examined in the same way as for any GLM.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] That is deviance residuals (or other standardized residuals) should be examined for patterns that might suggest a substantial violation of the independence or mean-variance assumptions of the model.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] This will usually involve plotting the standardized residuals against fitted values and covariates to look for mean-variance problems or missing pattern, and may also involve examining Correlograms (ACFs) and/or Variograms of the residuals to check for violation of independence.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] If the model mean-variance relationship is correct then scaled residuals should have roughly constant variance.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Note that since GLMs and GAMs can be estimated using Quasi-likelihood, it follows that details of the distribution of the residuals beyond the mean-variance relationship are of relatively minor importance.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] One issue that is more common with GAMs than with other GLMs is a danger of falsely concluding that data are zero inflated.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The one extra check that GAMs introduce is the need to check that the degrees of freedom chosen are appropriate.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] This is particularly acute when using methods that do not automatically estimate the smoothness of model components.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] When using methods with automatic smoothing parameter selection then it is still necessary to check that the choice of basis dimension was not restrictively small, although if the effective degrees of freedom of a term estimate is comfortably below its basis dimension then this is unlikely.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] In any case, checking $f_{j}(x_{j})$ is based on examining pattern in the residuals with respect to $x_{j}$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] This can be done using partial residuals overlaid on the plot of ${\hat {f}}_{j}(x_{j})$ , or using permutation of the residuals to construct tests for residual pattern.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] When smoothing parameters are estimated as part of model fitting then much of what would traditionally count as model selection has been absorbed into the fitting process: the smoothing parameters estimation has already selected between a rich family of models of different functional complexity.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] However smoothing parameter estimation does not typically remove a smooth term from the model altogether, because most penalties leave some functions un-penalized (e.g. straight lines are unpenalized by the spline derivative penalty given above).
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] So the question of whether a term should be in the model at all remains.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] One simple approach to this issue is to add an extra penalty to each smooth term in the GAM, which penalizes the components of the smooth that would otherwise be unpenalized (and only those).
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Each extra penalty has its own smoothing parameter and estimation then proceeds as before, but now with the possibility that terms will be completely penalized to zero.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] In high dimensional settings then it may make more sense to attempt this task using the lasso or elastic net regularization.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Boosting also performs term selection automatically as part of fitting.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] An alternative is to use traditional stepwise regression methods for model selection.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] This is also the default method when smoothing parameters are not estimated as part of fitting, in which case each smooth term is usually allowed to take one of a small set of pre-defined smoothness levels within the model, and these are selected between in a stepwise fashion.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Stepwise methods operate by iteratively comparing models with or without particular model terms (or possibly with different levels of term complexity), and require measures of model fit or term significance in order to decide which model to select at each stage.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] For example, we might use p-values for testing each term for equality to zero to decide on candidate terms for removal from a model, and we might compare Akaike information criterion (AIC) values for alternative models.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] P-value computation for smooths is not straightforward, because of the effects of penalization, but approximations are available.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] AIC can be computed in two ways for GAMs.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] The marginal AIC is based on the Marginal Likelihood (see above) with the model coefficients integrated out.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] In this case the AIC penalty is based on the number of smoothing parameters (and any variance parameters) in the model.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] However, because of the well known fact that REML is not comparable between models with different fixed effects structures, we can not usually use such an AIC to compare models with different smooth terms (since their un-penalized components act like fixed effects).
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Given these problems GAMs are often compared using the conditional AIC, in which the model likelihood (not marginal likelihood) is used in the AIC, and the parameter count is taken as the effective degrees of freedom of the model.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Overfitting can be a problem with GAMs, especially if there is un-modelled residual auto-correlation or un-modelled overdispersion.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Cross-validation can be used to detect and/or reduce overfitting problems with GAMs (or other statistical methods), and software often allows the level of penalization to be increased to force smoother fits.
[src:generalized-additive-models/generalized-additive-model] Where appropriate, simpler models such as GLMs may be preferable to GAMs unless GAMs improve predictive ability substantially (in validation sets) for the application in question.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] A **kernel smoother** is a statistical technique to estimate a real valued function $f:\mathbb {R} ^{p}\to \mathbb {R}$ as the weighted average of neighboring observed data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] The weight is defined by the *kernel*, such that closer points are given higher weights.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] The estimated function is smooth, and the level of smoothness is set by a single parameter.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] Kernel smoothing is a type of weighted moving average.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] Popular kernels used for smoothing include parabolic (Epanechnikov), tricube, and Gaussian kernels.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] Let $Y(X):\mathbb {R} ^{p}\to \mathbb {R}$ be a continuous function of *X*.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] In the following sections, we describe some particular cases of kernel smoothers.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] The Gaussian kernel is one of the most widely used kernels, and is expressed with the equation below.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] Here, b is the length scale for the input space.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] The *k*-nearest neighbor algorithm can be used for defining a ***k*-nearest neighbor smoother** as follows.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] For each point *X*0, take *m* nearest neighbors and estimate the value of *Y*(*X*0) by averaging the values of these neighbors.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] In this example, *X* is one-dimensional.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] For each X0, the ${\hat {Y}}(X_{0})$ is an average value of 16 closest to *X*0 points (denoted by red).
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] The idea of the kernel average smoother is the following.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] For each data point *X*0, choose a constant distance size *λ* (kernel radius, or window width for *p* = 1 dimension), and compute a weighted average for all data points that are closer than $\lambda$ to *X*0 (the closer to *X*0 points get higher weights).
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] For each *X*0 the window width is constant, and the weight of each point in the window is schematically denoted by the yellow figure in the graph.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] It can be seen that the estimation is smooth, but the boundary points are biased.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] The reason for that is the non-equal number of points (from the right and from the left to the *X*0) in the window, when the *X*0 is close enough to the boundary.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] In the two previous sections we assumed that the underlying Y(X) function is locally constant, therefore we were able to use the weighted average for the estimation.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] The idea of local linear regression is to fit locally a straight line (or a hyperplane for higher dimensions), and not the constant (horizontal line).
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] After fitting the line, the estimation ${\hat {Y}}(X_{0})$ is provided by the value of this line at *X*0 point.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] By repeating this procedure for each *X*0, one can get the estimation function ${\hat {Y}}(X)$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] Like in previous section, the window width is constant $h_{\lambda }(X_{0})=\lambda ={\text{constant}}.$ Formally, the local linear regression is computed by solving a weighted least square problem.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] The resulting function is smooth, and the problem with the biased boundary points is reduced.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] Local linear regression can be applied to any-dimensional space, though the question of what is a local neighborhood becomes more complicated.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] It is common to use k nearest training points to a test point to fit the local linear regression.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] This can lead to high variance of the fitted function.
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] To bound the variance, the set of training points should contain the test point in their convex hull (see Gupta et al. reference).
[src:generalized-additive-models/kernel-smoother] Instead of fitting locally linear functions, one can fit polynomial functions.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] LOESS and LOWESS thus build on "classical" methods, such as linear and nonlinear least squares regression.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] They address situations in which the classical procedures do not perform well or cannot be effectively applied without undue labor.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] LOESS combines much of the simplicity of linear least squares regression with the flexibility of nonlinear regression.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] It does this by fitting simple models to localized subsets of the data to build up a function that describes the deterministic part of the variation in the data, point by point.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In fact, one of the chief attractions of this method is that the data analyst is not required to specify a global function of any form to fit a model to the data, only to fit segments of the data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The trade-off for these features is increased computation.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Because it is so computationally intensive, LOESS would have been practically impossible to use in the era when least squares regression was being developed.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Most other modern methods for process modelling are similar to LOESS in this respect.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] These methods have been consciously designed to use our current computational ability to the fullest possible advantage to achieve goals not easily achieved by traditional approaches.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] A smooth curve through a set of data points obtained with this statistical technique is called a *loess curve*, particularly when each smoothed value is given by a weighted quadratic least squares regression over the span of values of the *y*-axis scattergram criterion variable.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] When each smoothed value is given by a weighted linear least squares regression over the span, this is known as a *lowess curve.* However, some authorities treat *lowess* and loess as synonyms.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Local regression and closely related procedures have a long and rich history, having been discovered and rediscovered in different fields on multiple occasions.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] An early work by Robert Henderson studying the problem of graduation (a term for smoothing used in Actuarial literature) introduced local regression using cubic polynomials.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Specifically, let $Y_{j}$ denote an ungraduated sequence of observations.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Following Henderson, suppose that only the terms from $Y_{-h}$ to $Y_{h}$ are to be taken into account when computing the graduated value of $Y_{0}$ , and $W_{j}$ is the weight to be assigned to $Y_{j}$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Solving these equations for the polynomial coefficients yields the graduated value, ${\hat {Y}}_{0}=a$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In preceding years, many 'summation formula' methods of graduation had been developed, which derived graduation rules based on summation formulae (convolution of the series of observations with a chosen set of weights).
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Two such rules are the 15-point and 21-point rules of Spencer (1904).
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] These graduation rules were carefully designed to have a quadratic-reproducing property: If the ungraduated values exactly follow a quadratic formula, then the graduated values equal the ungraduated values.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This is an important property: a simple moving average, by contrast, cannot adequately model peaks and troughs in the data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Henderson's insight was to show that *any* such graduation rule can be represented as a local cubic (or quadratic) fit for an appropriate choice of weights.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Further discussions of the historical work on graduation and local polynomial fitting can be found in Macaulay (1931), Cleveland and Loader (1995); and Murray and Bellhouse (2019).
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The Savitzky-Golay filter, introduced by Abraham Savitzky and Marcel J.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Golay (1964) significantly expanded the method.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Like the earlier graduation work, their focus was data with an equally-spaced predictor variable, where (excluding boundary effects) local regression can be represented as a convolution.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Savitzky and Golay published extensive sets of convolution coefficients for different orders of polynomial and smoothing window widths.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Local regression methods started to appear extensively in statistics literature in the 1970s; for example, Charles J.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Stone (1977), Vladimir Katkovnik (1979) and William S.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Katkovnik (1985) is the earliest book devoted primarily to local regression methods.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Theoretical work continued to appear throughout the 1990s.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Important contributions include Jianqing Fan and Irène Gijbels (1992) studying efficiency properties, and David Ruppert and Matthew P.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Wand (1994) developing an asymptotic distribution theory for multivariate local regression.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] An important extension of local regression is Local Likelihood Estimation, formulated by Robert Tibshirani and Trevor Hastie (1987).
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This replaces the local least-squares criterion with a likelihood-based criterion, thereby extending the local regression method to the Generalized linear model setting; for example binary data, count data or censored data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Practical implementations of local regression began appearing in statistical software in the 1980s.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Cleveland (1981) introduces the LOWESS routines, intended for smoothing scatterplots.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This implements local linear fitting with a single predictor variable, and also introduces robustness downweighting to make the procedure resistant to outliers.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] An entirely new implementation, LOESS, is described in Cleveland and Susan J.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] LOESS is a multivariate smoother, able to handle spatial data with two (or more) predictor variables, and uses (by default) local quadratic fitting.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Both LOWESS and LOESS are implemented in the S and R programming languages.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] See also Cleveland's Local Fitting Software.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] While Local Regression, LOWESS and LOESS are sometimes used interchangeably, this usage should be considered incorrect.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Local Regression is a general term for the fitting procedure; LOWESS and LOESS are two distinct implementations.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Local regression uses a data set consisting of observations one or more ‘independent’ or ‘predictor’ variables, and a ‘dependent’ or ‘response’ variable.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The dataset will consist of a number n observations.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The observations of the predictor variable can be denoted $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ , and corresponding observations of the response variable by $Y_{1},\ldots ,Y_{n}$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] For ease of presentation, the development below assumes a single predictor variable; the extension to multiple predictors (when the $x_{i}$ are vectors) is conceptually straightforward.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] A functional relationship between the predictor and response variables is assumed: $Y_{i}=\mu (x_{i})+\epsilon _{i}$ where $\mu (x)$ is the unknown ‘smooth’ regression function to be estimated, and represents the conditional expectation of the response, given a value of the predictor variables.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In theoretical work, the ‘smoothness’ of this function can be formally characterized by placing bounds on higher order derivatives.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The $\epsilon _{i}$ represents random error; for estimation purposes these are assumed to have mean zero.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Stronger assumptions (e.g., independence and equal variance) may be made when assessing properties of the estimates.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Local regression then estimates the function $\mu (x)$ , for one value of x at a time.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Since the function is assumed to be smooth, the most informative data points are those whose $x_{i}$ values are close to x .
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Questions of bandwidth selection and specification (how large should h be, and should it vary depending upon the fitting point x ?) are deferred for now.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] It is to be emphasized that the above procedure produces the estimate ${\hat {\mu }}(x)$ for one value of x .
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] When considering a new value of x , a new set of weights $w_{i}(x)$ must be computed, and the regression coefficient estimated afresh.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This matrix representation is crucial for studying the theoretical properties of local regression estimates.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] With appropriate definitions of the design and weight matrices, it immediately generalizes to the multiple-predictor setting.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The degree of local polynomial, or more generally, the form of the local model.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The choice of weight function $W(\cdot )$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The choice of fitting criterion (least squares or something else).
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Each of these components has been the subject of extensive study; a summary is provided below.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The bandwidth h controls the resolution of the local regression estimate.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] If *h* is too small, the estimate may show high-resolution features that represent noise in the data, rather than any real structure in the mean function.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Conversely, if *h* is too large, the estimate will only show low-resolution features, and important structure may be lost.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This is the *bias-variance tradeoff*; if *h* is too small, the estimate exhibits large variation; while at large *h*, the estimate exhibits large bias.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Careful choice of bandwidth is therefore crucial when applying local regression.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Mathematical methods for bandwidth selection require, firstly, formal criteria to assess the performance of an estimate.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] One such criterion is prediction error: if a new observation is made at ${\tilde {x}}$ , how well does the estimate ${\hat {\mu }}({\tilde {x}})$ predict the new response ${\tilde {Y}}$ ?
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Performance is often assessed using a squared-error loss function.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The second term, $\operatorname {E} \left[\mu (x)-{\hat {\mu }}({\tilde {x}})\right]^{2}$ is the mean squared estimation error.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This relation shows that, for squared error loss, minimizing prediction error and estimation error are equivalent problems.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In global bandwidth selection, these measures can be integrated over the x space ("mean integrated squared error", often used in theoretical work), or averaged over the actual $x_{i}$ (more useful for practical implementations).
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Mallow's Cp and Akaike's Information Criterion, which estimate mean squared estimation error.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Other methods which attempt to estimate bias and variance variance components of the estimation error directly.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Any of these criteria can be minimized to produce an automatic bandwidth selector.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Cleveland and Devlin prefer a graphical method (the *M*-plot) to visually display the bias-variance trade-off and guide bandwidth choice.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] One question not addressed above is, how should the bandwidth depend upon the fitting point x ?
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Often a constant bandwidth is used, while LOWESS and LOESS prefer a nearest-neighbor bandwidth, meaning *h* is smaller in regions with many data points.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Formally, the smoothing parameter, $\alpha$ , is the fraction of the total number *n* of data points that are used in each local fit.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The subset of data used in each weighted least squares fit thus comprises the $n\alpha$ points (rounded to the next largest integer) whose explanatory variables' values are closest to the point at which the response is being estimated.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] More sophisticated methods attempt to choose the bandwidth *adaptively*; that is, choose a bandwidth at each fitting point x by applying criteria such as cross-validation locally within the smoothing window.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Friedman's "supersmoother", which uses cross-validation to choose among local linear fits at different bandwidths.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Most sources, in both theoretical and computational work, use low-order polynomials as the local model, with polynomial degree ranging from 0 to 3.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The degree 0 (local constant) model is equivalent to a kernel smoother; usually credited to Èlizbar Nadaraya (1964) and G.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This is the simplest model to use, but can suffer from bias when fitting near boundaries of the dataset.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Local linear (degree 1) fitting can substantially reduce the boundary bias.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Local quadratic (degree 2) and local cubic (degree 3) can result in improved fits, particularly when the underlying mean function $\mu (x)$ has substantial curvature, or equivalently a large second derivative.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In theory, higher orders of polynomial can lead to faster convergence of the estimate ${\hat {\mu }}(x)$ to the true mean $\mu (x)$ , *provided that $\mu (x)$ has a sufficient number of derivatives*.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Generally, it takes a large sample size for this faster convergence to be realized.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] There are also computational and stability issues that arise, particularly for multivariate smoothing.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] It is generally not recommended to use local polynomials with degree greater than 3.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] As with bandwidth selection, methods such as cross-validation can be used to compare the fits obtained with different degrees of polynomial.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] As mentioned above, the weight function gives the most weight to the data points nearest the point of estimation and the least weight to the data points that are furthest away.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The use of the weights is based on the idea that points near each other in the explanatory variable space are more likely to be related to each other in a simple way than points that are further apart.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Following this logic, points that are likely to follow the local model best influence the local model parameter estimates the most.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Points that are less likely to actually conform to the local model have less influence on the local model parameter estimates.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Monotone: $W(x)$ is a nonincreasing function for $x\geq 0$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Asymptotic efficiency of weight functions has been considered by V.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Epanechnikov (1969) in the context of kernel density estimation; J.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Fan (1993) has derived similar results for local regression.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] They conclude that the quadratic kernel, $W(x)=1-x^{2}$ for $|x|\leq 1$ has greatest efficiency under a mean-squared-error loss function.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] See "kernel functions in common use" for more discussion of different kernels and their efficiencies.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Considerations other than MSE are also relevant to the choice of weight function.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Smoothness properties of $W(x)$ directly affect smoothness of the estimate ${\hat {\mu }}(x)$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In particular, the quadratic kernel is not differentiable at $x=\pm 1$ , and ${\hat {\mu }}(x)$ is not differentiable as a result.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The tri-cube weight function, $W(x)=(1-|x|^{3})^{3};|x|<1$ has been used in LOWESS and other local regression software; this combines higher-order differentiability with a high MSE efficiency.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] One criticism of weight functions with bounded support is that they can lead to numerical problems (i.e. an unstable or singular design matrix) when fitting in regions with sparse data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] For this reason, some authors choose to use the Gaussian kernel, or others with unbounded support.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] As described above, local regression uses a locally weighted least squares criterion to estimate the regression parameters.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] These disadvantages can be addressed by replacing the local least-squares estimation by something else.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Two such ideas are presented here: local likelihood estimation, which applies local estimation to the generalized linear model, and robust local regression, which localizes methods from robust regression.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] When $f(y,\theta (x))$ is the normal distribution and $\theta (x)$ is the mean function, the local likelihood method reduces to the standard local least-squares regression.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] For other likelihood families, there is (usually) no closed-form solution for the local likelihood estimate, and iterative procedures such as iteratively reweighted least squares must be used to compute the estimate.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] An asymptotic theory for local likelihood estimation is developed in J.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Heckman and M.P.Wand (1995); the book Loader (1999) discusses many more applications of local likelihood.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] To address the sensitivity to outliers, techniques from robust regression can be employed.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In local M-estimation, the local least-squares criterion is replaced by a criterion of the form $\sum _{i=1}^{n}w_{i}(x)\,\rho {\left({\frac {Y_{i}-\beta _{0}-\dots -\beta _{p}(x_{i}-x)^{p}}{s}}\right)}$ where $\rho (\cdot )$ is a robustness function and s is a scale parameter.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Discussion of the merits of different choices of robustness function is best left to the robust regression literature.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The scale parameter s must also be estimated.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] References for local M-estimation include Katkovnik (1985) and Alexandre Tsybakov (1986).
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The robustness iterations in LOWESS and LOESS correspond to the robustness function defined by $\rho '(u)=u(1-u^{2}/6)^{2};|u|<1$ and a robust global estimate of the scale parameter.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] When $p=0$ , this criterion is minimized by a locally weighted median; local $L_{1}$ regression can be interpreted as estimating the *median*, rather than *mean*, response.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] If the loss function is skewed, this becomes local quantile regression.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] A recent alternative is to modify the local regression weights rather than the loss function.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This provides robustness to outliers and high-leverage points without the multiple robustness iterations used in methods such as LOWESS and LOESS.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] As discussed above, the biggest advantage LOESS has over many other methods is the process of fitting a model to the sample data does not begin with the specification of a function.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Instead the analyst only has to provide a smoothing parameter value and the degree of the local polynomial.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In addition, LOESS is very flexible, making it ideal for modeling complex processes for which no theoretical models exist.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] These two advantages, combined with the simplicity of the method, make LOESS one of the most attractive of the modern regression methods for applications that fit the general framework of least squares regression but which have a complex deterministic structure.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Although it is less obvious than for some of the other methods related to linear least squares regression, LOESS also accrues most of the benefits typically shared by those procedures.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] The most important of those is the theory for computing uncertainties for prediction and calibration.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Many other tests and procedures used for validation of least squares models can also be extended to LOESS models .
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] LOESS makes less efficient use of data than other least squares methods.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] It requires fairly large, densely sampled data sets in order to produce good models.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This is because LOESS relies on the local data structure when performing the local fitting.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Thus, LOESS provides less complex data analysis in exchange for greater experimental costs.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Another disadvantage of LOESS is the fact that it does not produce a regression function that is easily represented by a mathematical formula.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] This can make it difficult to transfer the results of an analysis to other people.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In order to transfer the regression function to another person, they would need the data set and software for LOESS calculations.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In nonlinear regression, on the other hand, it is only necessary to write down a functional form in order to provide estimates of the unknown parameters and the estimated uncertainty.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Depending on the application, this could be either a major or a minor drawback to using LOESS.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] In particular, the simple form of LOESS can not be used for mechanistic modelling where fitted parameters specify particular physical properties of a system.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] Finally, as discussed above, LOESS is a computationally intensive method (with the exception of evenly spaced data, where the regression can then be phrased as a non-causal finite impulse response filter).
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] LOESS is also prone to the effects of outliers in the data set, like other least squares methods.
[src:generalized-additive-models/local-regression] There is an iterative, robust version of LOESS [Cleveland (1979)] that can be used to reduce LOESS' sensitivity to outliers, but too many extreme outliers can still overcome even the robust method; other non-iterative robust local regression methods have also been proposed.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] Let $\{x_{i},Y_{i}:i=1,\dots ,n\}$ be a set of observations, modeled by the relation $Y_{i}=f(x_{i})+\epsilon _{i}$ where the $\epsilon _{i}$ are independent, zero mean random variables.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] From these values, derive ${\hat {f}}(x)$ for all *x*.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] Given the vector ${\hat {m}}=({\hat {f}}(x_{1}),\ldots ,{\hat {f}}(x_{n}))^{T}$ of fitted values, the sum-of-squares part of the spline criterion is fixed.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] It remains only to minimize $\int {\hat {f}}''(x)^{2}\,dx$ , and the minimizer is a natural cubic spline that interpolates the points $(x_{i},{\hat {f}}(x_{i}))$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] where $f_{i}(x)$ are a set of spline basis functions.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] The basis functions, and hence the matrix A , depend on the configuration of the predictor variables $x_{i}$ , but not on the responses $Y_{i}$ or ${\hat {m}}$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] A is an $n\times n$ matrix given by $A=\Delta ^{T}W^{-1}\Delta$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] Minimizing over ${\hat {m}}$ by differentiating against ${\hat {m}}$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] De Boor's approach exploits the same idea, of finding a balance between having a smooth curve and being close to the given data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] where p is a parameter called smooth factor and belongs to the interval $[0,1]$ , and $\delta _{i};i=1,\dots ,n$ are the quantities controlling the extent of smoothing (they represent the weight $\delta _{i}^{-2}$ of each point $Y_{i}$ ).
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] In practice, since cubic splines are mostly used, m is usually 2 .
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] The solution for $m=2$ was proposed by Christian Reinsch in 1967.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] For $m=2$ , when p approaches 1 , ${\hat {f}}$ converges to the "natural" spline interpolant to the given data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] As p approaches 0 , ${\hat {f}}$ converges to a straight line (the smoothest curve).
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] Since finding a suitable value of p is a task of trial and error, a redundant constant S was introduced for convenience.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] The algorithm described by de Boor starts with $p=0$ and increases p until the condition is met.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] If $\delta _{i}$ is an estimation of the standard deviation for $Y_{i}$ , the constant S is recommended to be chosen in the interval $\left[n-{\sqrt {2n}},n+{\sqrt {2n}}\right]$ .
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] Having $S=0$ means the solution is the "natural" spline interpolant.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] Increasing S means we obtain a smoother curve by getting farther from the given data.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] There are two main classes of method for generalizing from smoothing with respect to a scalar x to smoothing with respect to a vector x .
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] The first approach simply generalizes the spline smoothing penalty to the multidimensional setting.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] The thin plate spline approach can be generalized to smoothing with respect to more than two dimensions and to other orders of differentiation in the penalty.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] As the dimension increases there are some restrictions on the smallest order of differential that can be used, but actually Duchon's original paper, gives slightly more complicated penalties that can avoid this restriction.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] The thin plate splines are isotropic, meaning that if we rotate the $x,z$ co-ordinate system the estimate will not change, but also that we are assuming that the same level of smoothing is appropriate in all directions.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] This is often considered reasonable when smoothing with respect to spatial location, but in many other cases isotropy is not an appropriate assumption and can lead to sensitivity to apparently arbitrary choices of measurement units.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] For example, if smoothing with respect to distance and time an isotropic smoother will give different results if distance is measure in metres and time in seconds, to what will occur if we change the units to centimetres and hours.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] The second class of generalizations to multi-dimensional smoothing deals directly with this scale invariance issue using tensor product spline constructions.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] Such splines have smoothing penalties with multiple smoothing parameters, which is the price that must be paid for not assuming that the same degree of smoothness is appropriate in all directions.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] Source code for spline smoothing can be found in the examples from Carl de Boor's book *A Practical Guide to Splines*.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] The examples are in the Fortran programming language.
[src:generalized-additive-models/smoothing-spline] The updated sources are available also on Carl de Boor's official site .
